.TH MOON 1 "2026-06-06" "moon-calendar" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
moon \- display today's lunar date
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B moon
.RI [ option ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Displays the current lunar date in natural language, e.g.
.IR "fourth moon day twenty\-two" .
.PP
The lunar year follows the Chinese calendar system: the first moon begins
on the second new moon after the winter solstice. Lunar days are anchored
to local calendar dates, so the new moon's day is always day one regardless
of the hour it occurs, and daylight saving time is accounted for
automatically.
.PP
On first run, the program asks for a location name and coordinates.
The location is used to determine the local timezone for accurate day
counting. Up to nine locations are saved in order of most recently used.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-o
Look up the lunar date for any date other than today. First shows the
location menu so the correct timezone is confirmed, then prompts for a
Gregorian calendar date in any common format (e.g.
.IR "2024-01-15" ,
.IR "Jan 15, 2024" ,
.IR "15 Jan 2024" ).
Dates from year 1 to 9999 CE are supported.
.TP
.B \-d
Print a plain-English lunar phase summary alongside the date. Reports
up to three things: any major phase that occurred in the past 36 hours
(e.g.
.IR "The full moon was yesterday at 11:42pm." ),
the next upcoming major phase with its day and time, and the next full
or new moon by day count \(em omitting the last item when it duplicates
the second. The four major phases are new moon, first quarter, full
moon, and last quarter. All times are in the local timezone derived from
the saved coordinates.
.TP
.B \-l
Open the location menu. Shows saved locations numbered 1\(en9 in
most-recently-used order. Enter a number to switch to that location,
.B 0
to add a new one, or
.B x
to delete a location.
.TP
.B \-r
Reset all saved locations. The next run will prompt for a new location.
.TP
.B \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a short summary of available commands and exit.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/moon-calendar/config.json
Saved locations in most-recently-used order.
.TP
.I ~/.local/bin/moon
Symlink to the script.
.SH EXAMPLES
Show today's lunar date:
.RS
.B moon
.RE
.PP
Show lunar date with phase details:
.RS
.B moon \-d
.RE
.PP
Look up the lunar date for a past or future date:
.RS
.B moon \-o
.RE
.PP
Switch or add a location:
.RS
.B moon \-l
.RE
.PP
Clear all saved locations:
.RS
.B moon \-r
.RE
